Other countries have also controlled the pandemic with intensive contact tracing, travel restrictions from abroad, testing and quarantine, but with less stringent confinement, such as Iceland and South Korea.
According to a statistical study, countries that have conducted more tests, in relation to the number of deaths, have much lower case fatality rates, probably because these countries have more ability to detect people who only have mild symptoms or who have no symptoms.
WHO recommends that non-testing countries with national laboratories with limited experience in COVID-19 submit their first five positive samples and their first ten negative samples for COVID-19 to any of WHO’s 16 reference laboratories for confirmatory testing.
Of the 16 reference laboratories, 7 are in Asia, 5 in Europe, 2 in Africa, 1 in North America and 1 in Australia.
